ἓ 2. 15. ad Atticum: in the extant letters to Atticus, the words here quoted do not occur. But in May 45 B.C., soon after the battle of Munda, Cicero wrote to Atticus from his villa at Tusculum thus : semz'lz'bcri saltem simus, quod adsequentur el tacendo et latendo (AdAtt. xiii 31, 3). Two explanations are possible. Either Cicero repeated this phrase in another letter, not extant, of the same time ; or Sen., remembering the one important word (semiliber), invented the rest of the sentence. Misquotation in ancient writers has wide limits: it has recently been suggested (by Mr F. W. Hall) that this inaccuracy is due in part to the great trouble of verifying quotations in rolls of the ancient form.
